    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1 Integrated Waste Management Fair conducted to raise awareness on plastic and waste management challenge and solution</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">First ever Ghana Integrated Waste Management Fair, also dubbed &#x201C;Ghana Waste Fair&#x201D; was held in July. The Fair had over 60 exhibitors, showcasing innovative solutions with different materials in transition and along the value chain. The fair also had thematic TED-TALK events, where over 150 participants (virtually and physically) featured issues from data and use in waste management, innovative solutions and impact of the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge, green finance, how financial and technical resources from development partners and donors can be leveraged to upscale integrated solutions for waste management, business clinics. A school&#x2019;s competition that was part of the fair concluded with St. Catherine Senior High School, Obuasi Senior High Technical School and Methodist Senior High School were awarded cash prizes to implement innovative solutions for waste management in their schools. Following the fair, a technical meeting with experts has enabled the drafting of policy and program recommendations and actions for policy advocacy with relevant government ministries and building partnerships for program implementation.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1 reviewed and revised communication and awareness strategies on plastic waste management to determine entry points, messages and platforms for communication. 
4 awareness and campaign messages and tools developed and deployed
At least 80 waste pickers pickers and collectors trained on good practices to reduce risk of COVID-19 infection in their work</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">UNDP and stakeholders under the auspices of the Waste Recovery Platform reviewed and revised the communication and awareness strategy of the platform. 

The communication outputs were 10 videos including 3 animations in 3 languages (English, Twi and Dagbani); 4 jingles translated in 3 languages (English, Twi, and Dagbani); 26 social media cards including 2 Gifs and messages.The jingles and video were aired on the 4 radio and 4 TV stations. In sum, TV and radio messages reached over 2.2million audience. Social media messages on both Facebook and Twitter reached about 150,000 audience. Over 2million people were reached with news story and social media posts on the training for waste pickers and collectors. Communications activities have contributed to increased recognition of waste collectors and waste pickers as relevant actors in Ghana&#x2019;s waste management value chain. 

The capacity of 100 leaders of waste pickers and collectors was improved, where UNDP, Women in Informal Employment: Globalizing and Organizing (WIEGO), Environmental Service Providers Association (ESPA) and Accra School of Hygiene conducted training of trainers for the waste pickers and collectors in Accra and Tema on good practices to reduce risk of COVID-19 infection.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
